Copyright is claimed only on the board layout, board appearance, and playing 
card appearances, but not on the rules and types of moves associated with 
playing cards. So many different games appear to have similar moves assigned 
to the same cards.

Anyone can make up their own rules of play. 

Other pursuit board games  

Courtesy of ChatGPT, here is its summary of a list of similar games, including 
its take on this game at the end!
1 Sorry! – Players move pawns around the board, sending opponents back to the 
start when landing on their space. The goal is to get all pawns home first.
2 Tock – A Canadian variation of Parcheesi played with playing cards instead 
of dice, where players race pegs around the board while sending opponents back 
to the start.
3 Headache – A game similar to Trouble, where players use a pop-o-matic die 
roller to move their pegs and send opponents back to the start. The goal is 
to get all pegs home.
4 Parcheesi – A classic racing game where players move their pawns around the 
board and send others back to the start by landing on the same space. 
Originates from the ancient game Pachisi.
5 Ludo – A simplified version of Parcheesi popular worldwide, where players 
race their pawns to the finish while trying to block or capture opponents.
6 Aggravation – Players race their marbles around the board, "aggravating" 
opponents by sending them back to start. The first player to get all their 
marbles home wins.
7 Frustration – Similar to Ludo but with a pop-o-matic die roller, where 
players race to get their pawns home while blocking others.
8 Trouble – A classic pop-o-matic game where players race their pegs to home 
while sending opponents back to the start by landing on their space.
9 Pachisi – The ancient Indian game that inspired Parcheesi, where players 
race their pawns around the board and use strategy to capture opponents.
10 Mensch ärgere Dich nicht – A German board game similar to Ludo, where 
players race their pawns around the board, sending opponents back to start if 
they land on the same space.
11 Sorry! Sliders – A hybrid of Sorry! and shuffleboard, where players slide 
their pawns to knock opponents off the board or send them back to start.
12 Chaupar – A more complex Indian game related to Pachisi, played on a 
cross-shaped board with dice and pawns, involving strategic moves and 
capturing opponents.
13 Super Tock 6 – A variation of Tock played with teams, where players use 
cards to move pegs and help teammates while sending opponents back.
14 Uckers – A naval board game similar to Ludo, traditionally played in the 
Royal Navy, with rules for capturing and blocking opponents.
15 Royal Game of Ur – One of the oldest known board games, featuring a race 
where players move their pieces around a board and aim to capture opponents.
16 Pegs and Jokers – A card-based variation of Tock where players race pegs 
to home, using strategy and teamwork to block opponents and send them back.
17 Parqués – A Colombian version of Parcheesi with slight rule variations, 
where players race pawns and send opponents back to the start by landing on 
the same space.
18 Petits Chevaux – A French race game similar to Ludo and Parcheesi, 
featuring horse-shaped pieces racing to the finish.
19 Kimble – A Finnish variation of Trouble, complete with a pop-o-matic die, 
where players race pegs to the home zone while sending opponents back.
20 Kraków – A Polish variation of Ludo played on a custom board, where players 
race their pawns to the finish while hindering others.
21 The Game of Goose – A centuries-old race game where players move around a 
spiral board, facing obstacles and setbacks as they race to the center.
22 Revenge at Hay Lake – An adult version of Sorry!, played with cards, where 
players race to get their pawns home while strategically seeking vengeance by 
sending opponents back to the start. It's a race fueled by revenge, not 
apologies.    